{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6f724f6e-4e2e-4f6f-b830-d12b0f6e3b69","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the easiest option for .NET apps and doesn't require installing heavy tools like PerfView or ETW directly.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level + .NET combined ETW traces |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live check (`cpu-usage`, `threadpool-queue-length`) before committing to a full trace |\n| **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** | Deep native + kernel analysis |\n\n### Quick triage first:\n\n```powershell\n# See live counters without a trace\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nThis instantly shows CPU usage, GC pressure, thread pool stats, and exception rate — often enough to narrow the problem before collecting a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"75da2eab-faa1-45c5-ac85-4d6cbda8494f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":388},"id":"b6478825-f754-4d5e-a179-40b81d0008e8","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:51:17.875Z","parentId":"e254f6dd-8a27-4d53-b127-e17d55b7e0f8"}
